en_content:
A total of 20 health plan operators will have ten days to respond to the National Consumer Secretariat (Senacon) of the Ministry of Justice and Public Security on unilateral cancellations of contracts in recent days. The folder notified companies amid a significant increase in the number of consumer complaints.
According to the Ministry of Justice, the ProConsumidor system registered 231 complaints; the National Consumer Protection Information System (Sindec Nacional) had 66 occurrences; and the consumer platform. gov.br received 1.753 complaints about unilateral cancellations of contracts. The folder highlights that the volume of complaints indicates a growing concern among consumers, especially those in situations of vulnerability, such as patients in continuous treatment for serious conditions such as cancer and autism.
In addition to the systems of the Ministry of Justice, the National Supplementary Health Agency (ANS) recorded a significant increase in the number of Preliminary Research Notifications (NIPs). The notifications, informed the ministry, were made on the basis of the Consumer Protection Code and Article 5 of the Constitution, which ensures consumer protection as a fundamental right and principle of economic order.
According to National Consumer Secretary, Wadih Damous, the ministry is committed to ensuring transparency and security in the relationship between health operators and consumers, taking strict measures to curb abuse. The unilateral termination of contracts in a short time, highlights Senacon, prevents the search for viable alternatives, becoming more serious in the case of beneficiaries who need continuous or long-term assistance that suddenly become without essential medical coverage.
Operators have up to ten days to send their answers to Senacon through physical or electronic protocol. Companies should use the “Intercurrent Competition” tool, available on the Ministry of Justice and Public Security website.
